               LuminousMoth – PlugX, File Exfiltration and Persistence Revisited
            </h1> <div class="tw-mt-3 tw-items-center tw-text-sm sm:tw-flex"><div class="sm:tw-w-1/3"><div class="tw-mt-2.5 tw-flex tw-flex-wrap tw-items-center tw-text-sm"><a href="/en-us/blog/labs/author/vvrabie" title="Victor VRABIE" class="tw-overflow-hidden tw-rounded-full tw-h-11 tw-w-11"><img width="50" height="50" alt="Victor VRABIE" title="Victor VRABIE" data-src="https://blogapp.bitdefender.com/labs/content/images/size/w100/2021/05/vvrabie-150x150.png" class="tw-h-full tw-w-full tw-object-cover"></a> <div class="tw-pl-2"><div><a href="/en-us/blog/labs/author/vvrabie" title="Victor VRABIE" class="tw-mr-1.5 last:tw-mr-0">Victor VRABIE
         </a></div> <p class="tw-text-[#41485e]">
         July 21, 2021
      </p></div> <!----> <!----></div></div> <div class="tw-mt-4 sm:tw-mt-0 sm:tw-w-2/3"><div class="tw-relative tw-rounded tw-bg-[#f4f7fa] tw-py-2 tw-pl-11 tw-pr-2 tw-text-xs"><em class="tw-absolute tw-left-2.5 tw-top-2 tw-text-[10px]">Promo</em> <span class="pe-2">Protect all your devices, without slowing them down.</span> <br> <a target="_blank" href="/Downloads/" class="tw-text-[#608dff]">Free 30-day trial</a></div></div></div> <picture class="tw-my-6"><source data-not-lazy="" media="(max-width: 600px)" data-srcset="https://blogapp.bitdefender.com/labs/content/images/size/w600/2021/07/antivirus-5930412_1920.jpg"> <source data-not-lazy="" media="(min-width: 701px)" data-srcset="https://blogapp.bitdefender.com/labs/content/images/size/w1000/2021/07/antivirus-5930412_1920.jpg"> <img data-not-lazy="" data-src="https://blogapp.bitdefender.com/labs/content/images/size/w600/2021/07/antivirus-5930412_1920.jpg" alt="LuminousMoth – PlugX, File Exfiltration and Persistence Revisited" title="LuminousMoth – PlugX, File Exfiltration and Persistence Revisited" width="600" height="400" src="https://blogapp.bitdefender.com/labs/content/images/size/w600/2021/07/antivirus-5930412_1920.jpg" class="tw-my-4 tw-w-full"></picture> <div class="content tw-mb-12 tw-text-lg tw-text-black"><h2 id="foreword">Foreword</h2><p>A few months ago, Bitdefender researchers started to investigate an extended operation that targeted victims from Myanmar and Thailand for what looked like cyber espionage and intelligence gathering.</p><p>Many aspects of this operation were recently comprehensively described in <a href="https://securelist.com/apt-luminousmoth/103332/" rel="noreferrer noopener">this</a> article by the Kaspersky team, but we decided to present our perspective on the operation and offer other IOCs we spotted.</p><p>The investigation started with our usual triage process where we observed suspicious activity of two processes; <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\WinWord.exe</code> and <code>C:\ProgramData\Msolutions\svmetrics.exe</code>. As a result, we were able to identify an infection vector and we collected the tools and TTPs specific to this operation.</p><p>We analyzed the chain of events and traced the start of the infection on some victims to the file <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\Downloads\COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(MOTC)\COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe</code>, the creation of which corresponds to 2020-11-12 08:21. This file is a legitimate WinWord.exe executable vulnerable to sideloading.</p><p>The actions on behalf of this <code>COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe</code> we were able to reconstruct are:</p><ul><li>It copies itself as <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\WinWord.exe</code></li><li>It installs persistence by creating the “Microsof” key value under the Run registry assigning the <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\WinWord.exe</code> value</li><li>It starts communicating with the CobaltStrike C&amp;C <code>www.updatecatalogs.com</code></li></ul><p>More details on tools and TTPs can be found in the sections below.</p><h2 id="key-findings">Key Findings </h2><ul><li>Previously-unreported payload in the form of the well-known Remote Access Tool PlugX</li><li>Data exfiltration carried through Google Drive</li><li>More tools used for data collection</li><li>the attackers perform HTML code injection using ARP spoofing to redirect the victim to a page hosted by the threat actor</li><li>Extra findings suggesting that LuminousMoth is connecting to Mustang Panda</li><li>Some more examples of binaries vulnerable to sideloading used in this attack</li><li>Some more examples of persistence mechanisms</li><li>More IOCs associated with this operation</li></ul><h2 id="fmtoptionsdll-and-plugx">Fmtoptions.dll and Plugx</h2><p>We were able to link the <code>C:\ProgramData\Msolutions\svmetrics.exe</code> process with the <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\WinWord.exe</code>, and with the current operation, as we have evidence that svmetrics.exe executed more than once the <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\WinWord.exe</code> file, the one that was initially copied by the <code>COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe</code> alongside the malicious wwlib.dll.</p><p>The svmetrics.exe (InternalName from version info: <code>fmtoptions.exe</code>) is vulnerable to sideloading and is abused to load <code>Fmtoptions.dll</code>.</p><p>Analyzing the malicious Fmtoptions.dll file, we established that they read the content of a <code>walk.dat</code> file and decrypt the shellcode that is, subsequently, executed.  The shellcode is responsible for decompressing and loading the final payload, the PlugX  implant, that represents a DLL with the damaged MZ and PE magic values. More details on the recovered payloads are presented in the following table:</p><!--kg-card-begin: html--><table class="Table  Ltr TableGrid BorderColorBlack TransparentBackgroundColor TableWordWrap  BCX0 SCXW89496369" border="1" data-tablestyle="MsoTableGrid" data-tablelook="1696" aria-rowcount="3" style="margin: 0px auto; It starts scanning for files in the folders Documents, Desktop and Downloads belonging to the specified user in the “FLIN” string. It also scans for files on all drives except the <code>C:\</code> drive and all CDROM ones.</p><p>Another technical detail worthy of note is the mechanism used to ensure that all files are unique in the staging folder. The MD5 hash for each file is calculated and it is checked if the hash is not contained in a vector with all previous hashes. If not, it will be stored in the vector and will be written into the <code>C:\Users\Public\Downloads\Background-Intelligent-Transfer-Service.bin</code> file as a hex string. Each time the DLL is executed, the content of the file with MD5 hashes is parsed and the vector of hashes is populated. The targeted files are those with the following extensions:</p><!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><pre><code>.doc, .docx, .pdf, .xlsx, .exe
</code></pre>
<!--kg-card-end: markdown--><p>A noteworthy turn took place on 2021-03-09 when the svmetrics.exe executed another interesting piece of malware – <code>C:\Users\&lt;username&gt;\AppData\Roaming\Zoom\ZoomVideoApp.exe</code>. The <code>ZoomVideoApp.exe</code> implements the same collection function, but with more features, as it automatically archives the staging folder and exfiltrates the files to the C&amp;C. The sample was analyzed in Kaspersky's blogpost.</p><p>There are many differences between the <code>http_dll.dll</code> and <code>ZoomVideoApp.exe</code>, but both of these samples use an ini file for customizing the behavior, the common parameters by functionality being “meeting” and “ssb_sdk” as they are equivalent to the “CreateRAM” and “ModifyRAM”, respectively.</p><p>The deployment of the <code>ZoomVideoApp.exe</code> can be interpreted as an update to the collection and exfiltration mechanism, as for the files collected by the http_dll.dll, the attackers were forced to manually archive and exfiltrate the files.</p><h2 id="file-exfiltration">File Exfiltration</h2><p>The attackers deployed another piece of malware to exfiltrate files, as we noticed the execution of a binary from an unusual location having an archive name and an authentication token as parameters from the command line.  The files were put into an archive created using the rar.exe utility.</p><p>The process <code>C:\Kpcms\Send1.exe</code> was executed multiple times by the <code>svmetrics.exe</code>. After analysis, we concluded that the sample uploads the files to Google Drive as it uses the endpoint <code>https://www.googleapis.com/upload/drive/v3/files?uploadType=media</code> to perform a simple upload. According to the documentation of the endpoint, it is used for the transfer of files that are smaller than 5MB. To bypass this limitation, the attackers were forced to split the archive into multiple parts and upload each one as suggested by the archives names that we encounter.</p><p>This limitation was fixed into a new version of the tool as the attackers start to use another sample, <code>C:\ProgramData\Adobe\Send3.exe</code>, for the same purpose. The major improvement of the tool was the use of a resumable upload mechanism to upload files bigger than 5MB. New command line parameters were introduced like the one for specifying the chunk size, which allows the uploading of the file by performing multiple HTTP PUT operations. There is also an option for resuming an upload by specifying the <code>UploadID</code> and for checking if the upload was successful.</p><p>After the deploying ZoomVideoApp.exe, the tool wasn’t seen in use anymore, probably because of the exfiltration capabilities of the ZoomVideoApp.exe.</p><h2 id="arpspoof-and-html-injection">ArpSpoof and html injection</h2><p>After finding that svmetrics.exe executed the <code>C:\ProgramData\Adobe\Send3.exe</code> and <code>C:\ProgramData\Adobe\GetChromeCookies.exe</code> on one victim, we took a closer look on files from the <code>C:\ProgramData\Adobe\</code> as it seems to be a location where the attackers staged many tools. As a result, we noticed the <code>C:\ProgramData\adobe\arpspoof.exe</code> file.</p><p>Our analysis of this file found that the location path links to the attackers, and found many other details that will be mentioned below.</p><p>Thanks to the RTTI information, we established that the arpspoof.exe is actually a modified build of <a href="https://github.com/sin5678/zxarps" rel="noreferrer noopener"><code>https://github.com/sin5678/zxarps</code></a> and it was customized to receive from command line an IP and a PORT and to inject a HTML code into the HTTP responses received from that <code>IP:PORT</code> using the ARP spoofing and packet capturing using Winpcap. The particular HTML is hardcoded into the binary itself and is similar to:</p><!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><pre><code>&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;script&gt;window.location.href=&quot;http://microsoft.updatecatalogs[.]com/Microsoft Update Catalog.htm&quot;&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>
<!--kg-card-end: markdown--><p>We analyzed the sample and compared it with the code from GitHub, and we noticed another custom modification in the <strong><code>CARPSpoof::HackHtml</code></strong> function:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="data:image/png;base64," class="kg-image" alt loading="lazy"></figure><p>As can be seen from the image, the HTML will be injected only into the responses that have the 200-status code and don’t contain the strings </p><!--kg-card-begin: markdown--><pre><code>“2.58.230.5”, “content-google:” and “X-AspNet-Version: 4.0.30319\r\n”
</code></pre>
<!--kg-card-end: markdown--><p>The injected HTML intends to redirect the user to <strong><code>http://microsoft.updatecatalogs.com/Microsoft Update Catalog.htm</code> </strong>- a web page belonging to the attackers, as the domain <strong><code>updatecatalogs.com</code> </strong>is a known C&amp;C for the Cobalt Strike beacon.</p><p>Another interesting thing is the <strong><code>2.58.230.5</code></strong> IP and the fact that the tool skips injection into the http responses from that IP, probably because that IP was part of the attacker’s infrastructure. Moreover, at the time of this writing, the domain <strong><code>new.mmtimes.org</code></strong> is resolved to that IP and it is pretty similar to the <strong><code>mmtimes.net</code> </strong>found in the PlugX sample. The <strong><code>mmtimes.org</code> </strong>was already mentioned in the Kaspersky report as being used in earlier operations performed by Mustang Panda, and therefore, the arpspoof.exe, the malicious URL <strong><code>http://microsoft.updatecatalogs[.]com/Microsoft Update Catalog.htm</code> </strong>from the injected HTML code and the <strong><code>2.58.230.5</code></strong> IP address to which the domain <strong><code>mmtimes.org</code></strong> resolves to, suggest that the LuminousMoth and Mustang Panda, are connected.</p><h2 id="more-sideloading">More sideloading</h2><p>There are certainly more tools used by actors in this operation as, beside the fmtoptions.exe, WinWord.exe and igfxEM.EXE files vulnerable to sideloading, we found two other vulnerable binaries abused to load a malicious DLL file.</p><p>The first case we want to address is <code>C:\Users\Public\Music\VSTOInstaller.exe</code>, which was executed by the same svmetrics.exe. This sample of Visual Studio Tools for Office Solution Installer loads the vstoloader.dll and the malicious DLL loaded this way is <code>C:\Users\Public\music\vstoloader.dll</code> that extracts a shellcode from the <strong><code>ret.bin</code> </strong>file and executes it. Unfortunately, we weren’t able to obtain the <strong><code>ret.bin</code></strong> file, so we don’t know what role the tool might have.</p><p>Being executed by the same svmetrics.exe process, the <code>C:\Intel\install\stay\AtlTraceTool8.exe</code> is another legitimate binary abused by the attackers. The only thing we were able to establish about this binary is that it loads the malicious <code>C:\Intel\install\stay\1033\ AtlTraceToolUI.dll</code>, but the file could not be obtained.</p><h2 id="persistence">Persistence</h2><p>The data we gathered suggests at least two of the tools we encounter are setting up persistence:</p><!--kg-card-begin: html--><table class="Table  Ltr TableGrid BorderColorBlack TransparentBackgroundColor TableWordWrap  BCX0 SCXW89496369" border="1" data-tablestyle="MsoTableGrid" data-tablelook="1696" aria-rowcount="3" style="margin: 0px; {layout:"default",data:[{post:{id:"66d5c3d2d0ec1aefc7d72297",uuid:"e48cbad0-6800-465d-9c82-cb1b0eb9fa7c",title:C,slug:"luminousmoth-plugx-file-exfiltration-and-persistence-revisited",html:"\u003Ch2 id=\"foreword\"\u003EForeword\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA few months ago, Bitdefender researchers started to investigate an extended operation that targeted victims from Myanmar and Thailand for what looked like cyber espionage and intelligence gathering.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany aspects of this operation were recently comprehensively described in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fsecurelist.com\u002Fapt-luminousmoth\u002F103332\u002F\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003Ethis\u003C\u002Fa\u003E article by the Kaspersky team, but we decided to present our perspective on the operation and offer other IOCs we spotted.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe investigation started with our usual triage process where we observed suspicious activity of two processes; \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\WinWord.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E and \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Msolutions\\svmetrics.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E. As a result, we were able to identify an infection vector and we collected the tools and TTPs specific to this operation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe analyzed the chain of events and traced the start of the infection on some victims to the file \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\&lt;user&gt;\\Downloads\\COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(MOTC)\\COVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, the creation of which corresponds to 2020-11-12 08:21. This file is a legitimate WinWord.exe executable vulnerable to sideloading.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe actions on behalf of this \u003Ccode\u003ECOVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E we were able to reconstruct are:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIt copies itself as \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\WinWord.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIt installs persistence by creating the “Microsof” key value under the Run registry assigning the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\WinWord.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E value\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIt starts communicating with the CobaltStrike C&amp;C \u003Ccode\u003Ewww.updatecatalogs.com\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore details on tools and TTPs can be found in the sections below.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"key-findings\"\u003EKey Findings \u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPreviously-unreported payload in the form of the well-known Remote Access Tool PlugX\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EData exfiltration carried through Google Drive\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMore tools used for data collection\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ethe attackers perform HTML code injection using ARP spoofing to redirect the victim to a page hosted by the threat actor\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExtra findings suggesting that LuminousMoth is connecting to Mustang Panda\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESome more examples of binaries vulnerable to sideloading used in this attack\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESome more examples of persistence mechanisms\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMore IOCs associated with this operation\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"fmtoptionsdll-and-plugx\"\u003EFmtoptions.dll and Plugx\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe were able to link the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Msolutions\\svmetrics.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E process with the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\WinWord.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, and with the current operation, as we have evidence that svmetrics.exe executed more than once the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\WinWord.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E file, the one that was initially copied by the \u003Ccode\u003ECOVID-19 Case 12-11-2020(1).exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E alongside the malicious wwlib.dll.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe svmetrics.exe (InternalName from version info: \u003Ccode\u003Efmtoptions.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E) is vulnerable to sideloading and is abused to load \u003Ccode\u003EFmtoptions.dll\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnalyzing the malicious Fmtoptions.dll file, we established that they read the content of a \u003Ccode\u003Ewalk.dat\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E file and decrypt the shellcode that is, subsequently, executed.  The shellcode is responsible for decompressing and loading the final payload, the PlugX  implant, that represents a DLL with the damaged MZ and PE magic values. color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\u003C\u002Ftd\u003E\u003C\u002Ftr\u003E\u003C\u002Ftbody\u003E\u003C\u002Ftable\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-end: html--\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe malware, then, creates a folder using the current time and the format string \u003Ccode\u003E“%Y-%m-%d %H-%M-%S”\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E in the \u003Ccode\u003E“C:\\Users\\Public\\Downloads\\”\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E where all files will be staged. It starts scanning for files in the folders Documents, Desktop and Downloads belonging to the specified user in the “FLIN” string. It also scans for files on all drives except the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E drive and all CDROM ones.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother technical detail worthy of note is the mechanism used to ensure that all files are unique in the staging folder. The MD5 hash for each file is calculated and it is checked if the hash is not contained in a vector with all previous hashes. If not, it will be stored in the vector and will be written into the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Downloads\\Background-Intelligent-Transfer-Service.bin\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E file as a hex string. Each time the DLL is executed, the content of the file with MD5 hashes is parsed and the vector of hashes is populated. The targeted files are those with the following extensions:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-begin: markdown--\u003E\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode\u003E.doc, .docx, .pdf, .xlsx, .exe\n\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fpre\u003E\n\u003C!--kg-card-end: markdown--\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA noteworthy turn took place on 2021-03-09 when the svmetrics.exe executed another interesting piece of malware – \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\&lt;username&gt;\\AppData\\Roaming\\Zoom\\ZoomVideoApp.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E. The \u003Ccode\u003EZoomVideoApp.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E implements the same collection function, but with more features, as it automatically archives the staging folder and exfiltrates the files to the C&amp;C. The sample was analyzed in Kaspersky's blogpost.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are many differences between the \u003Ccode\u003Ehttp_dll.dll\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E and \u003Ccode\u003EZoomVideoApp.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, but both of these samples use an ini file for customizing the behavior, the common parameters by functionality being “meeting” and “ssb_sdk” as they are equivalent to the “CreateRAM” and “ModifyRAM”, respectively.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe deployment of the \u003Ccode\u003EZoomVideoApp.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E can be interpreted as an update to the collection and exfiltration mechanism, as for the files collected by the http_dll.dll, the attackers were forced to manually archive and exfiltrate the files.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"file-exfiltration\"\u003EFile Exfiltration\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe attackers deployed another piece of malware to exfiltrate files, as we noticed the execution of a binary from an unusual location having an archive name and an authentication token as parameters from the command line.  The files were put into an archive created using the rar.exe utility.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe process \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Kpcms\\Send1.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E was executed multiple times by the \u003Ccode\u003Esvmetrics.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E. After analysis, we concluded that the sample uploads the files to Google Drive as it uses the endpoint \u003Ccode\u003Ehttps:\u002F\u002Fwww.googleapis.com\u002Fupload\u002Fdrive\u002Fv3\u002Ffiles?uploadType=media\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E to perform a simple upload. According to the documentation of the endpoint, it is used for the transfer of files that are smaller than 5MB. To bypass this limitation, the attackers were forced to split the archive into multiple parts and upload each one as suggested by the archives names that we encounter.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis limitation was fixed into a new version of the tool as the attackers start to use another sample, \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Adobe\\Send3.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, for the same purpose. The major improvement of the tool was the use of a resumable upload mechanism to upload files bigger than 5MB. New command line parameters were introduced like the one for specifying the chunk size, which allows the uploading of the file by performing multiple HTTP PUT operations. There is also an option for resuming an upload by specifying the \u003Ccode\u003EUploadID\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E and for checking if the upload was successful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the deploying ZoomVideoApp.exe, the tool wasn’t seen in use anymore, probably because of the exfiltration capabilities of the ZoomVideoApp.exe.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"arpspoof-and-html-injection\"\u003EArpSpoof and html injection\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter finding that svmetrics.exe executed the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Adobe\\Send3.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E and \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Adobe\\GetChromeCookies.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E on one victim, we took a closer look on files from the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\Adobe\\\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E as it seems to be a location where the attackers staged many tools. As a result, we noticed the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\ProgramData\\adobe\\arpspoof.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E file.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOur analysis of this file found that the location path links to the attackers, and found many other details that will be mentioned below.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThanks to the RTTI information, we established that the arpspoof.exe is actually a modified build of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fsin5678\u002Fzxarps\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Ehttps:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fsin5678\u002Fzxarps\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and it was customized to receive from command line an IP and a PORT and to inject a HTML code into the HTTP responses received from that \u003Ccode\u003EIP:PORT\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E using the ARP spoofing and packet capturing using Winpcap. The particular HTML is hardcoded into the binary itself and is similar to:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-begin: markdown--\u003E\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode\u003E&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;script&gt;window.location.href=&quot;http:\u002F\u002Fmicrosoft.updatecatalogs[.]com\u002FMicrosoft Update Catalog.htm&quot;&lt;\u002Fscript&gt;&lt;\u002Fbody&gt;&lt;\u002Fhtml&gt;\n\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fpre\u003E\n\u003C!--kg-card-end: markdown--\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe analyzed the sample and Moreover, at the time of this writing, the domain \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Enew.mmtimes.org\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E is resolved to that IP and it is pretty similar to the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Emmtimes.net\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Efound in the PlugX sample. The \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Emmtimes.org\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Ewas already mentioned in the Kaspersky report as being used in earlier operations performed by Mustang Panda, and therefore, the arpspoof.exe, the malicious URL \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Ehttp:\u002F\u002Fmicrosoft.updatecatalogs[.]com\u002FMicrosoft Update Catalog.htm\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Efrom the injected HTML code and the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003E2.58.230.5\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E IP address to which the domain \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Emmtimes.org\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E resolves to, suggest that the LuminousMoth and Mustang Panda, are connected.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"more-sideloading\"\u003EMore sideloading\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are certainly more tools used by actors in this operation as, beside the fmtoptions.exe, WinWord.exe and igfxEM.EXE files vulnerable to sideloading, we found two other vulnerable binaries abused to load a malicious DLL file.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first case we want to address is \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\Music\\VSTOInstaller.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, which was executed by the same svmetrics.exe. This sample of Visual Studio Tools for Office Solution Installer loads the vstoloader.dll and the malicious DLL loaded this way is \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Users\\Public\\music\\vstoloader.dll\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E that extracts a shellcode from the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Eret.bin\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Efile and executes it. Unfortunately, we weren’t able to obtain the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Eret.bin\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E file, so we don’t know what role the tool might have.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeing executed by the same svmetrics.exe process, the \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Intel\\install\\stay\\AtlTraceTool8.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E is another legitimate binary abused by the attackers. The only thing we were able to establish about this binary is that it loads the malicious \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Intel\\install\\stay\\1033\\ AtlTraceToolUI.dll\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, but the file could not be obtained.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"persistence\"\u003EPersistence\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe data we gathered suggests at least two of the tools we encounter are setting up Malware",slug:"infected-minecraft-mods-lead-to-multi-stage-multi-platform-infostealer-malware",feature_image:"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2023\u002F06\u002Fminecraft-1106252_1920.jpg",featured:d,published_at:"2023-06-08T20:00:00.000+03:00",custom_excerpt:a,html:"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJune 9 Update:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe oldest sample we were able to track until now (\u003Ccode\u003Ee69b50d1d58056fc770c88c514af9a82\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E) shows the malware during its early development stage. Dated 2023-04-12, it looks like a Stage 2 sample with the C&amp;C address set to \u003Ccode\u003E127.0.0.1\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, which leads us to believe that it was used for testing. It also includes limited functionality that currently is available in Stage 3 samples (only listening for OS commands (executed with  \u003Ccode\u003Eexec\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E) ), which reinforces our assumption that the malware was in development at that time.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe also noticed that the Java package was named differently back in April ( \u003Ccode\u003Edev.sirlennox.nekoclient\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E  instead of  \u003Ccode\u003Edev.neko.nekoclient\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E). \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe also identified several executables (NekoInstaller\u002FNekoService), as described below:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENekoInstaller contains a Portable Executable file named NekoServices; at execution it drops the executable file in  \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Program Files\\nekoservice\\ServiceHost.exe\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E  and adds it as a service named  \u003Ccode\u003ENekoService\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E  to run;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENekoService contains a JAR file as a resource; it will download a JRE and run the JAR file; the JAR file is then dropped in  \u003Ccode\u003EC:\\Program Files\\nekoservice\\service.jar\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ethe JAR file seems to be a Stage 2 sample\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ethe MZ header compilation time for most of these samples ranges between 2023-04-20 18:20:06 and 2023-05-01 22:17:25, and just one sample was identified to be compiled on 2023-05-21 07:58:12, which means that the malware was in development in that timeframe.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBased on this evidence, it seems that the attackers initially planned to distribute EXE files rather than JAR ones, but we were unable to assess whether the EXE files have been disseminated in the wild or not.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial article:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral Minecraft mods and plugins hosted on the CurseForge and Bukkit modding communities \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fblog\u002Fhotforsecurity\u002Ffractureiser-malware-discovered-in-minecraft-mods-spreading-uncertainty\u002F\"\u003Ehave been tainted\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with a multi-stage, multi-platform infostealer malware called Fractureiser, a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Ffractureiser-investigation\u002Ffractureiser\u002Fblob\u002Fmain\u002Fdocs\u002Ftech.md\"\u003Epreliminary investigation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E shows.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral CurseForge and Bukkit accounts have been compromised and used to publish malware-rigged updates of mods and plugins without the knowledge of the original author. These mods have trickled downstream into popular modpacks that have been downloaded several million times to date.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe malware has 4 stages, labeled 0 through 3. Stage 0 is considered the modified mod or plugin to include obfuscated code that connects to \u003Ccode\u003Ehttp:\u002F\u002F85.217.144.130:8080\u002Fdl\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E to download the Stage 1 malware.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Stage 1 malware comes in the form of a dl.jar file with a SHA-1 sum of \u003Ccode\u003Edc43c4685c3f47808ac207d1667cc1eb915b2d82\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E. The Stage 1 malware includes a mutex to prevent it from running multiple times, and it seems responsible for infecting other JAR files, establishing persistence and contacting the command and control server in preparation of Stage 2 deployment.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 2 (lib.jar or libWebGL64.jar) acts as a downloader and updater for the final payload in Stage 3.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 3 brings the final payload, in the form of a jar file that includes a native binary named hook.dll. Hook.dll is exposing two functionalities that are called from Java code: \u003Ccode\u003EretrieveClipboardFiles\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E - to retrieve file descriptors from the clipboard, used for the virtual machine escape technique (detailed below), as well as \u003Ccode\u003EretrieveMSACredentials\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E to retrieve Microsoft Live credentials.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"what-we-know-so-far\"\u003EWhat we know so far\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first sample apparently dates all the way back to April 24th 2023 in the form of a Stage 0 malware with the \u003Ccode\u003E0e583c572ad823330b9e34d871fcc2df\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E hash. The first JAR (Java Archive) file lacks many of the features currently in the malware.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe malware currently affects Linux and Windows Minecraft installs and attempts to inject itself into all other eligible .jar files on the system, including those that are not part of a Minecraft mod. The malware has a complex logic to determine whether a .jar file is a candidate for infection. Upon modification of the file, the infection code also disables code signing for Java files by removing the \u003Ccode\u003EMETA-INF\u002FCERTIFIC.RSA\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003EMETA-INF\u002FCERTIFIC.EC\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003EMETA-INF\u002FCERT.SF\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E and \u003Ccode\u003EMETA-INF\u002FCERTIFIC.SF\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe malware monitors the clipboard for crypto-currency wallet addresses, then swaps them with the attacker’s to hijack transactions. It also steals Minecraft and Discord authentication tokens, as well as cookies and login data stored in the most popular browsers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring our analysis, we identified interesting behavior we believe is aimed at mod or plugin developers. It looks like the Stage 3 malware targets Windows Sandbox instances used for testing mods by monitoring and constantly poisoning the clipboard in an attempt to infect the host. This behavior is isolated to Windows Sandbox, as it is the only virtualization environment that allows alteration of the host clipboard contents when the virtual machine is running in the background.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe were able to confirm that dozens of mods and plugins have been rigged with the malware. The affected mods are listed in the Indicators of Compromise section below.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe overwhelming majority of victims are in the US. We are monitoring the individual components of this malware and will update the threat distribution accordingly.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"mitigation\"\u003EMitigation\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBitdefender identifies the malicious code in all stages of execution as \u003Ccode\u003ETrojan.Java.Fractureiser.*\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E. If you have downloaded any of the infected mods in recent months or have any concern about the integrity of your .jar files, run a deep scan with your favorite security solution such as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fsolutions\u002Ftotal-security.html\"\u003EBitdefender Total Security\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 Portable, frequently updated and relatively inexpensive when compared to a new smart TV, these devices offer a convenient, cost-effective, and customizable way to access a vast selection of content from the comfort of your own home. Smart TVs and streaming devices account for \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fblog\u002Fhotforsecurity\u002Fa-smart-device-in-your-home-is-extremely-unsafe-iot-report-finds\u002F\"\u003Ea whopping 20%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E [pdf] of all connected IoT devices, and potential vulnerabilities in firmware could affect a significant user base.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the creator of the world’s first smart home cybersecurity hub, Bitdefender regularly audits popular IoT hardware for vulnerabilities that might affect customers if left unaddressed. This research paper is part of a broader program and aims to shed light on the security of the world’s best-sellers in the IoT space. This report covers the Amazon Fire TV Stick and the Insignia\u003Cbr\u003EFireOS TV products. The research discloses vulnerabilities affecting the following products and versions:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInsignia TV with FireOS versions before \u003Ccode\u003E6.2.9.5\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E \u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFire TV Stick 3rd gen. with FireOS versions before \u003Ccode\u003E7.6.3.3\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENote: the vulnerabilities presented in this report have been responsibly disclosed to the vendor through their Bug Bounty program. Amazon has released fixes for these issues on Fire TV devices and the Fire TV remote app, and the company has no evidence that this issue has been used against customers. Bitdefender has been working closely with the Amazon Fire TV team through all stages of vulnerability disclosure. We would like to extend our thanks for the prompt response time, communication, transparency and escalation.\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"vulnerabilities-at-a-glance\"\u003EVulnerabilities at a glance\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUnauthorized authentication through local network PIN brute forcing. This vulnerability was caused by improper implementation of the Password Authenticated Key Exchange by Juggling (or J-PAKE) protocol that could have resulted in attackers gaining control of the device. (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcve.mitre.org\u002Fcgi-bin\u002Fcvename.cgi?name=CVE-2023-1385\"\u003ECVE-2023-1385\u003C\u002Fa\u003E)\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA vulnerability in the setMediaSource function on the amzn.thin.pl service allowed for arbitrary Javascript code to be executed. It could be used to load arbitrary HTTP URLs in the webview. (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcve.mitre.org\u002Fcgi-bin\u002Fcvename.cgi?name=CVE-2023-1384\"\u003ECVE-2023-1384\u003C\u002Fa\u003E)\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA vulnerability in the exchangeDeviceServices function on the amzn.dmgr service allowed an attacker to register services that are only locally accessible. (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcve.mitre.org\u002Fcgi-bin\u002Fcvename.cgi?name=CVE-2023-1383\"\u003ECVE-2023-1383\u003C\u002Fa\u003E)\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-begin: markdown--\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"disclosure-timeline\"\u003EDisclosure timeline\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\n\u003C!--kg-card-end: markdown--\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDec 16, 2022 - Bitdefender researchers submit the findings to the bug bounty program\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDec 19, 2022: Bug bounty program submits the report for vendor to review\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDec 20, 2022: Amazon team acknowledges the findings and starts an internal investigation\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EApr 12, 2023: Amazon delivers the fix to the public\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EApr 13, 2023: A bounty is awarded for the findings\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMay 2, 2023: This report is published as part of the coordinated disclosure\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-begin: html--\u003E\u003Cp align=\"center\"\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Ffiles\u002FNews\u002FCaseStudies\u002Fstudy\u002F430\u002FBitdefender-PR-Whitepaper-AMZFr-creat6696-en-EN.pdf\" class=\"button-view-all d-inline-block\"\u003EDownload the research paper\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003C!--kg-card-end: html--\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"best-practices-for-iot-devices\"\u003EBest practices for IoT devices\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHome users should closely monitor IoT devices and isolate them as much as possible from the local network. This can be done by setting up a dedicated network exclusively for IoT devices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, IoT users can use the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fsolutions\u002Fhome-scanner.html\"\u003Efree Bitdefender Smart Home Scanner\u003C\u002Fa\u003E app to scan for connected devices, identify and highlight vulnerable ones. Smart TVs and streaming devices account for a whopping 20% [pdf] of all connected IoT devices, and potential vulnerabilities in firmware could affect a significant user base.\n\nAs",reading_time:N,url:"\u002Fblog\u002Flabs\u002Fvulnerabilities-identified-amazon-fire-tv-stick-insignia-fire-os-tv-series\u002F"},{id:"66d5c3d2d0ec1aefc7d722b5",title:"EyeSpy - Iranian Spyware Delivered in VPN Installers",slug:"eyespy-iranian-spyware-delivered-in-vpn-installers",feature_image:"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2023\u002F01\u002Feyespy-1.jpg",featured:d,published_at:"2023-01-11T13:00:00.000+03:00",custom_excerpt:a,html:"\u003Cp\u003EConsumer VPN solutions have witnessed explosive growth in the past few years. These ubiquitous utilities help users keep their internet traffic private, surf anonymously, and bypass restrictions or censorship. And, while most of the world takes this technology for granted,  users in specific regions - such as the people in Iran - have to try out dozens of apps before they find one that is (still) able to bypass ISP restrictions. And, while some VPNs are fake [\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fblog\u002Fhotforsecurity\u002Fhow-to-identify-a-fake-vpn\u002F\"\u003Ehere is a guide on how to spot a fake VPN app\u003C\u002Fa\u003E] or blocked, some others are deliberately laced with malware. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContext\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring routine analysis of detection performance, we noticed a batch of processes that respected the same pattern in the process names. These names begin with \u003Cem\u003Esys,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Cem\u003Ewin\u003C\u002Fem\u003E or \u003Cem\u003Elib\u003C\u002Fem\u003E followed by a word that describes the functionality, such as \u003Cem\u003Ebus\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, \u003Cem\u003Ecrt\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, \u003Cem\u003Etemp\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, \u003Cem\u003Ecache\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, \u003Cem\u003Einit\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, and end in \u003Cem\u003E32.exe\u003C\u002Fem\u003E. We later noticed that the .bat files and the downloaded payloads respect the same naming convention. Further investigation revealed the components are part of a monitoring application called SecondEye, developed in Iran and distributed legitimately via the developer’s website. We also found that some spyware components were already described in an article published by \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblackpointcyber.com\u002Fresources\u002Fblog\u002Feye-spy-the-dangers-of-legal-malware\u002F \"\u003EBlackpoint\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. In the article, researchers drew attention to the dangers of legally distributed monitoring software with malicious behavior.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOur own researchers, as well as Blackpoint’s, found the campaigns used components of the SecondEye suite and their infrastructure. However, these components were not delivered through a legitimate SecondEye installer but rather through Trojanized installers of VPN software (also developed in Iran) that dropped the spyware components along with the VPN product.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttack at a glance\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBitdefender has discovered a malware campaign that uses components of SecondEye - a legitimate monitoring application - to spy on users of 20Speed VPN, an Iranian-based VPN service, via trojanized installers.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEyeSpy has the ability to fully compromise online privacy via keylogging and stealing of sensitive information, such as documents, images, crypto-wallets, and passwords.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe campaign started in May 2022, but detections peaked in August and September. Most of these detections originate from Iran, with a small pool of victims in Germany and the US.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndicators of Compromise\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn up-to-date, complete list of indicators of compromise is available to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Foem\u002Fadvanced-threat-intelligence.html\"\u003EBitdefender Advanced Threat Intelligence\u003C\u002Fa\u003E users. From fake job offers and elaborate phishing schemes to scams and even state-sponsored threat actors who prey on people’s career aspirations and trust in professional networks.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo shed light on such scenarios, this article delves into the deceptive tactics of a failed \"recruitment\" operation on LinkedIn, where the attackers made one critical mistake: they targeted a Bitdefender researcher who quickly uncovered their malicious intent.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"the-setup-a-tempting-job-offer\"\u003EThe Setup: A Tempting Job Offer\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe scam begins with an enticing message: an opportunity to collaborate on a decentralized cryptocurrency exchange. While the details are left deliberately vague, the promise of remote work, part-time flexibility, and reasonable pay can lure unsuspecting individuals. Variations of this scam have also been observed, with projects supposedly related to travel or financial domains.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F1--1---1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"405\" height=\"354\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the target expresses interest, the \"hiring process\" unfolds, with the scammer requesting a CV or even a personal GitHub repository link. Although seemingly innocent, these requests can serve nefarious purposes, such as harvesting personal data or lending a veneer of legitimacy to the interaction.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F2--1---1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"302\" height=\"112\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe submitted files provided by the “applicant” are most definitely put to good use by the “recruiter” who can harvest information and use it to further legitimize the conversation with the unsuspecting victim.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F3--1---1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"433\" height=\"161\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"the-trap-running-the-malicious-code\"\u003EThe Trap: Running the Malicious Code\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter receiving the requested information, the criminal shares a repository containing the \"minimum viable product\" (MVP) of the project. He also includes a document with questions that can only be answered by executing the demo.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F4--1---1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"382\" height=\"394\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F5--1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"388\" height=\"392\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt first glance, the code appears harmless. However, closer inspection reveals a heavily obfuscated script that dynamically loads malicious code from a third-party endpoint.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F6--1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"602\" height=\"83\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F6--1-.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F6--1-.png 602w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F7.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"602\" height=\"78\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F7.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F7.png 602w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOur researchers noted that the payload is a cross-platform info-stealer that can be deployed on Windows, MacOS and Linux operating systems. This infostealer is engineered to target a range of popular cryptocurrency wallets by looking up for the crypto-related browsing extensions with the following IDs:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002Fimage.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"975\" height=\"670\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2025\u002F02\u002Fimage.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2025\u002F02\u002Fimage.png 975w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce deployed, the stealer collects important files corresponding to these extensions while also collecting login data of the used browsers and exfiltrates the information to a malicious IP address that seems to contain other malicious files on the server. After exfiltrating login and extension-related data, the JavaScript stealer downloads and executes a Python script named main99_65.py that sets the stage for other malicious activities.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Python script decompresses and decodes itself recursively until it finally reveals the next stage - a hidden script that further enables the download of three additional Python modules:&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Emlip.py\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHooks keyboard events specifically targeting web browsers.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMonitors clipboard changes system-wide for crypto-related data.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EImmediately sends stolen data to a remote attacker-controlled server.&nbsp;\u003Cbr\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Epay.py\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EReports system\u002Fnetwork info to the attacker.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESearches for and exfiltrates valuable files (documents, environment variables, private keys, crypto mnemonics) and uploads these files to the attacker’s C2 server.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMaintains a persistent communication channel for additional commands and scripts.&nbsp;\u003Cbr\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Ebow.py\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIterates over the following browsers: Chrome, Brave, Opera, Yandex, Microsoft Edge&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExtracts and exfiltrates sensitive browser data (logins and payment info) for Windows, Linux, and macOS&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERuns the Tsunami Injector python script that connects to multiple Pastebins to reach the URL for the payload (.exe 617205f5a241c2712d4d0a3b06ce3afd)&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next payload in line (a .NET binary) proceeds to further drop dependencies alongside the main payload. One of the dependencies adds malicious binaries to the exception list of Microsoft Defender, while also downloading and starting a Tor Proxy Server to communicate with the Command &amp; Control (C2) server. Furthermore, the binary also downloads another malicious executable from the Tor C2, installs .NET 6.0 if it is not already installed, and exfiltrates the following fingerprinting information about the victim:&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EName of the host\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUsername\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOperating system\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProcessor name and core count\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGPU name\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERAM information\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPublic IP &amp; Country &amp; City\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe executable downloaded from the Tor C2 server contains multiple modules that are run on different threads:&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBackdoor – performs a wide range of data-collection operations (browser passwords, sessions, crypto wallet keys, discord account secrets);&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E“Secret file” stealer – a configurable stealer that scans and exfiltrates files based on designated rules fetched from the C2 server;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECrypto-miner – also configurable. It can be throttled based on certain monitored metrics (CPU &amp; GPU load, CPU cores, RAM amount, ongoing activity);&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EKeylogger – uses the win32 APIs to capture, store and exfiltrate keystrokes.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe threat actors' infection chain is complex, containing malicious software written in multiple programming languages and using a variety of technologies, such as multi-layered Python scripts that recursively decode and execute themselves, a JavaScript stealer that first harvests browser data before pivoting to further payloads, and.NET-based stagers capable of disabling security tools, configuring a Tor proxy, and launching crypto miners.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe malware infects Windows, macOS, and Linux via cross-platform compatibility, uses a variety of exfiltration methods (HTTP, Tor, and attacker-controlled IPs), and includes modules for keylogging, system reconnaissance, file harvesting, and continuous C2 communication, demonstrating the breadth and complexity of its capabilities.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"the-mastermind-a-state-sponsored-threat-actor\"\u003EThe Mastermind: A State-Sponsored Threat Actor\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnalysis of the malware and operational tactics strongly suggests the involvement of state-sponsored threat actors, specifically those from North Korea. These actors, previously linked to malicious job offers and fake job applications, have ties to groups like the Lazarus Group (APT 38).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETheir objectives go beyond personal data theft. By compromising people working in sectors such as aviation, defense, and nuclear industries, they aim to exfiltrate classified information, proprietary technologies, and corporate credentials. In this case, executing the malware on enterprise devices could grant attackers access to sensitive company data, amplifying the damage.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile in this article, we’ve discussed malicious job offers, it has been observed that the same threat actors have tried to infiltrate various companies by faking identities and applying for a multitude of job positions. The result would be approximately the same: private information, credentials, and technology would be exfiltrated by corporate spies.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn up-to-date, complete list of indicators of compromise is available to&nbsp;\u003Cstrong\u003EBitdefender Advanced Threat Intelligence\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E&nbsp;users&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fintellizone.bitdefender.com\u002Fen\u002Fthreat-search\u002Fthreats\u002FBDqtp2wovl\" rel=\"noreferrer\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Ehere\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"how-to-stay-safe\"\u003EHow to Stay Safe\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs social platforms increasingly become hotspots for malicious activities, vigilance is essential. Here are some red flags and measures to protect yourself:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed Flags:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVague job descriptions:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E No corresponding job posting on the platform.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuspicious repositories:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Belong to users with random names and lack proper documentation or contributions.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor communication:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Frequent spelling errors and refusal to provide alternative contact methods, such as corporate emails or phone numbers.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBest Practices:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid running unverified code:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Use virtual machines, sandboxes, or online platforms to test code safely.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerify authenticity:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Cross-check job offers with official corporate websites and confirm email domains.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdopt a cautious mindset:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Scrutinize unsolicited messages and requests for personal information.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is ideal to never execute any foreign source code on enterprise devices, and to use Virtual Machines, sandboxes or various online platforms when doing so on personal computers. These campaigns use fake advertisements to lure users into installing malicious software disguised as legitimate apps or updates.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the more recent campaigns Bitdefender Labs uncovered involves a fake Bitwarden extension advertised on Meta’s social media platform Facebook. The campaign tricks users into installing a harmful browser extension under the guise of a security update.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKey findings include:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatform Exploitation:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Attackers are leveraging Facebook’s advertising platform to deliver ads that look legitimate but lead to a malicious website.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpersonation of Reputable Brands:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E The campaign impersonates Bitwarden, a popular password manager, to build trust and create a sense of urgency by prompting users to install a supposed \"security update.\"\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecific Target Demographics: \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003ELaunched on Nov 3, 2024, this campaign specifically targets consumers aged 18 to 65 across Europe.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent Reach and Global Expansion Potential:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E The malicious ads have already been served to thousands of users, and could expand further. If left unchecked, this campaign could scale globally, affecting users worldwide.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse of Redirect Chains: \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EUsers who click on these ads are redirected through multiple sites, ultimately landing on a phishing page that mimics the official Chrome Web Store to obscure the ad’s malicious intent.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EData Collection on Business and Personal Accounts:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E The malware gathers personal data and targets Facebook business accounts, potentially leading to financial losses for individuals and businesses.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce again, this campaign highlights how threat actors exploit trusted platforms like Facebook to lure users into compromising their own security. By masquerading as a reputable tool and imitating urgent update notifications, cybercriminals gain access to valuable personal and business information.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThanks to Bitdefender Labs’ research, we now have a clearer understanding of the evolving tactics used in this type of attacks:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Step One: Fake Ads to Lure Users In\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe attack begins with a deceptive Facebook ad that warns users that their passwords are at risk and urges them to update their Bitwarden browser extension. &nbsp;The ad looks legitimate, using Bitwarden branding and urgent language, such as \"Warning: Your Passwords Are at Risk!\" to push users into action.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClicking on the ad takes users to a fake webpage designed to mimic the official Chrome Web Store. When users click \"Add to Chrome,\" they are redirected to a Google Drive link containing a zip file with the malicious extension. Attackers guide users through a process to install the extension by:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUnzipping the file\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGoing to their browser’s extension settings via chrome:\u002F\u002Fextensions\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEnabling Developer Mode\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EManually loading the unpacked extension (sideloading).\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis method manipulates users into bypassing browser security checks, allowing the malware to install without detection.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2. Malicious Extension Details: Full Access and Suspicious Permissions\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce installed, the malicious extension requests extensive permissions that allow it to intercept and manipulate the user’s online activities. A closer look at the extension’s manifest file reveals permissions to operate on all websites, modify network requests, and access storage and cookies. Key aspects of the manifest include:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"name\": \"Bitwarden Password Manager\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"manifest_version\": 3,\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"background\": {\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"service_worker\": \"service-worker-loader.js\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"type\": \"module\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; },\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"permissions\": [\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"contextMenus\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"storage\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"cookies\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"tabs\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"declarativeNetRequest\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"webNavigation\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"webRequest\",\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \"management\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe extension’s \u003Cstrong\u003Eservice-worker-loader.js\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E script initiates \u003Cstrong\u003Ebackground.js\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E, the primary component driving the malicious operations. Additionally, \u003Cstrong\u003Epopup.js\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E—an obfuscated script—loads when users click the extension icon in their browser, enabling it to:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eaccess cookies from https:\u002F\u002Ffacebook.com, specifically seeking the c_user cookie containing the Facebook user ID.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003Emanipulate the page’s DOM elements to display fake loading messages, creating an illusion of legitimate actions.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3. Background Worker: Collecting and Exfiltrating Data\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebackground.js\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E script, which activates upon installation, is the core of this attack.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003Echrome.runtime.onInstalled.addListener(async details =&gt; {\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; getFacebookCookies();\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E});\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;Here’s how it operates:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECookie Harvesting\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Upon installation, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebackground.js\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E calls getFacebookCookies() to check for Facebook cookies. If found, it gathers further data using the collectData() function.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIP and Geolocation Data Collection\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: The extension queries IP and location data via https:\u002F\u002Fapi.ipify.org and https:\u002F\u002Ffreeipapi.com.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook Data Extraction\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Through Facebook’s Graph API, the malware retrieves user data, including:\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPersonal details like user ID and name\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBusiness accounts and ad account information\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECredit card and billing details associated with ad accounts\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce collected, the data is sent to a Google Script URL, which acts as the command-and-control (C2) server for the attackers. The \u003Cstrong\u003EsendData()\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E function handles data exfiltration by encoding and transmitting sensitive information.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4. Detection and Defense Strategies\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDetecting and mitigating this attack is a challenge for cybersecurity teams due to its reliance on legitimate platforms like Facebook and Google Drive. Here are some detection ideas for security professionals:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitor Suspicious Permissions\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: declarativeNetRequest and webRequest permissions, paired with access to cookies, are strong indicators of potential malware.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBehavioral Signatures\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Obfuscated functions like chrome.runtime.onInstalled.addListener and calls to graph.facebook.com APIs can serve as indicators of compromise (IoCs).\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"safety-tips-for-users\"\u003ESafety Tips for Users\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo protect yourself from similar malvertising campaigns, follow these essential security tips:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerify Extension Updates\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Always update extensions directly through official browser stores (e.g., Chrome Web Store) rather than by clicking on ads or third-party links.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrutinize Ads and Links\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Be cautious of sponsored ads on social media, especially those calling for immediate action or updates for security tools.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECheck Extension Permissions\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Before installing or updating an extension, review its permissions. Extensions requesting access to cookies, network requests, or all website data may be malicious.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnable Security Features\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Use browser security settings, such as disabling Developer Mode when not in use, to prevent unauthorized sideloading of extensions.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReport Suspicious Ads\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: If you encounter misleading or malicious ads on social media, report them to the platform to help prevent the spread of similar attacks.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Fol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \u003Cstrong\u003EUse a Security Solution\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Protect yourself from malvertising and phishing attacks by using a reliable security solution like \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bitdefender.com\u002Fen-us\u002Fconsumer\u002Ftotal-security\" rel=\"noreferrer\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBitdefender Total Security\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Cybercriminals have a knack for exploiting the engine that powers online platforms by corrupting the vast reach of advertising to distribute malware en masse. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile legitimate businesses rely on ads to reach new audiences, hackers exploit these platforms to trick users into downloading harmful software. Malicious ads often seem to promote legitimate software, streaming services, or products, making it difficult for users to distinguish between safe and dangerous content.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBitdefender Labs has been tracking malvertising for years, analyzing how cybercriminals use these tactics to target people across the globe. Our latest research focuses on a growing campaign leveraging Meta’s advertising platform to spread SYS01 InfoStealer malware.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis ongoing attack impersonates popular brands to distribute malware that steals personal data, The scale and sophistication of this malvertising campaign highlight how far cybercriminals have come in weaponizing ads for their own gain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this article, we’ll explore how the SYS01 campaign works, the cybercriminal model that fuels it, and how hackers use hijacked accounts to keep the operation running. We’ll also offer some crucial tips on how users can protect against it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch3 id=\"key-findings\"\u003EKey Findings:\u003C\u002Fh3\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOngoing Attack\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: The malvertising campaign that has been wreaking havoc on Meta platforms for at least a month is continuously evolving, with new ads appearing daily. The SYS01 InfoStealer malware has become a central weapon in this campaign, effectively targeting victims across multiple platforms.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectronJs Delivery and Broadened Impersonation\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Compared to previous malvertising campaigns, the SYS01 malware is now delivered through an ElectronJs application. To maximize reach, threat actors have begun impersonating a wide range of well-known software tools, increasing the likelihood of targeting a broader user base.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensive Use of Malicious Domains\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: The malvertising campaign leverages nearly a hundred malicious domains, utilized not only for distributing the malware but also for live command and control (C2) operations, allowing threat actors to manage the attack in real time.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMass Brand Impersonation\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: The hackers behind the campaign use trusted brands to expand their reach. Bitdefender Labs researchers noticed hundreds of ads impersonating popular video editing software like CapCut, productivity tools like Office 365, video streaming services such as Netflix, and even video games are being used to entice users. The widespread impersonation increases the likelihood of drawing in a broad audience, making the campaign highly effective.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobal Reach\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: The scope of this attack is global, with potential victims in the millions, spanning regions such as the EU, North America, Australia, and Asia – particularly males aged 45 and above. While Meta provides some data on ad impact within the EU, there is limited transparency on how these malicious ads are affecting users outside this region, especially in the US.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDynamic Evasion Tactics\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Threat actors continuously evolve their strategies, adapting malicious payloads almost in real time to avoid detection. Once antivirus companies detect and block a version of the malware dropper, hackers enhance obfuscation methods and re-launch new ads with updated versions.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"the-malicious-advertising-campaign\"\u003EThe malicious advertising campaign\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile malware distributed through social media ads is not an innovation in the criminal cyberspace, a campaign that started in September stood out through the malicious samples that were distributed and because of the generic impersonation approach used by the cybercriminals. Bitdefender has previously analyzed infostealers that were distributed through ads that impersonated Artificial Intelligence software or that promised “provocative” content.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the current campaign, the threat actors impersonate a multitude of software tools related to productivity, video or photo editing (Capcut, Canva, Adobe Photoshop), virtual private networks (Express VPN, VPN Plus) movie streaming services such as Netflix, instant messaging software such as Telegram and even video games.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome ads might end up running for weeks, targeting mainly senior men.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fphotoshop_87k--1-.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\"
