https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fphotoshop_87k--1-.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of what video games were impersonated, we have observed two approaches. The first was promoting Super Mario Bros Wonder advertisements, directly offering malicious samples.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FScreenshot-2024-10-03-154256--1--1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1443\" height=\"536\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FScreenshot-2024-10-03-154256--1--1.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw1000\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FScreenshot-2024-10-03-154256--1--1.png 1000w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FScreenshot-2024-10-03-154256--1--1.png 1443w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second approach was reusing malicious domains, that impersonated a generic video game download platform (containing well known titles or recent hits like Black Myth: Wukong). The threat actors also changed the download mechanism newer samples that were similar to the ones obtained from previous ads.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fblue_games--1--1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1533\" height=\"586\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fblue_games--1--1.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw1000\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fblue_games--1--1.png 1000w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fblue_games--1--1.png 1533w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsidering the multitude of impersonated entities, the number of distributed ads, which is in the thousands, and the reach of particular ads of tens of thousands of people, it would be safe to say that this malicious advertising infrastructure could reach millions of people. Even if most of the audience does not interact with the advertisements or does not download the malicious samples, such a large potential victim pool virtually guarantees success.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"distribution-tactics-of-the-sys01-infostealer-malvertising-campaign\"\u003E&nbsp;Distribution Tactics of the SYS01 Infostealer Malvertising Campaign\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ads typically point to a \u003Cstrong\u003EMediaFire\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E link or refer to one that allows the direct download of malicious software. The samples are obtained in the form of a \u003Cem\u003E.zip \u003C\u002Fem\u003Earchive which contains an Electron application. While the structure of the extracted archive might differ, depending on the sample, the infection method remains the same: the Javascript code embedded in the Electron app will end up dropping and executing malicious software.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads6.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"536\" height=\"235\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn many cases, the malware runs in the background while a decoy app—often mimicking the ad-promoted software—appears to function normally, making it difficult for the victim to realize they’ve been compromised.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FPicture17.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1088\" height=\"808\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FPicture17.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw1000\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FPicture17.png 1000w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FPicture17.png 1088w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApplications created using the Electron framework are bundled into ASAR archives (\u003Cem\u003EAtom Shell Archive Format\u003C\u002Fem\u003E). All extracted archives either contained an \u003Cem\u003Eapp.asar \u003C\u002Fem\u003Efile, or directly included the ASAR file into the main executable. The ASAR archive contains, besides the usual application icons, plenty of suspicious files:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAnother archive that is password protected;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA legitimate archiving\u002Funarchiving executable (for example, 7za.exe - c136b1467d669a725478a6110ebaaab3cb88a3d389dfa688e06173c066b76fcf, which is a standalone version of 7zip);\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA \u003Cem\u003Emain.js \u003C\u002Fem\u003Efile which contains obfuscated code;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E[Optional] PowerShell scripts used as intermediaries;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA text file containing well-known GPU models.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon deobfuscating the JavaScript file, it becomes apparent that a PowerShell command is used to execute standalone 7zip, enabling the extraction of the password-protected archive.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads7.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"47\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads7.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads7.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe executed PowerShell script contains another execution command between some seemingly unrelated operations (used to avoid detection and\u002For further complicate analysis):\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads8.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"302\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads8.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads8.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, before doing this, the \u003Cem\u003Emain.js\u003C\u002Fem\u003E script checks if it is executed in a sandbox by enumerating the GPUs of the host:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads9.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"130\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads9.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads9.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe response of the PowerShell command is then cross-checked with the GPU models contained in the packed text file. If the GPU model is not in the predefined list, nothing malicious ends up being executed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENewer versions of the malicious main.js directly execute the unzipping process, skipping the intermediary PowerShell scripts \u003Cem\u003E(_0x3ddef2 \u003C\u002Fem\u003Eleads to the 7zip executable)\u003Cem\u003E:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads10.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"56\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads10.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads10.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, the script triggers the start of another process using a PHP interpreter and a PHP script which were part of the password-protected archive that was extracted before.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads11.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"145\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads11.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads11.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe PHP samples are encoded using the IonCube Loader, making malware analysis difficult. Typically, two malicious samples are found in the extracted content: \u003Cem\u003Eindex.php \u003C\u002Fem\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003Einclude.php\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, with some samples containing \u003Cem\u003Etest.php\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads12.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"343\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads12.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads12.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the malware gets past the point of checking whether it ran in a sandbox, the first executed script would be \u003Cem\u003Einclude.php.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E This script enables persistence of the malware through the Task Scheduler by creating two tasks:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWDNA\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E - Ensures the periodic run of the PHP infostealer through the command \u003Cem\u003Erhc.exe php.exe index.php. \u003C\u002Fem\u003EThis task is executed every two minutes, starting with the date at which the script was first executed.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWDNA_LG \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E– At every logon of the user that executed the malware, run both the \u003Cem\u003Einclude.php \u003C\u002Fem\u003Escript (re-ensuring persistence in case it is somehow altered) and \u003Cem\u003Eindex.php.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;Analyzing a memory dump of the \u003Cem\u003Ephp.exe index.php \u003C\u002Fem\u003Eprocess reveals several interesting facts:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe `SYS01` string appears several times;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThere are plenty of C2 domains that the malware can use;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMore domains can even be obtained through the use of Telegram bots or Google pages;\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads13.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"167\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads13.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads13.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads14.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"437\" height=\"147\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe process uses the SQL commands that can have malicious intentions, for example `\u003Cem\u003E SELECT * FROM moz_cookies`\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESeveral URLs leading to Facebook and some of its APIs, further indicating that gaining intel about Facebook accounts, especially business pages, remains one of the goals of the infostealer.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe infostealer seems to communicate with either the hardcoded C2 domains or the ones obtained dynamically by using Telegram Bots and Google Pages by simple commands. For example, the C2 can be checked if it is up by doing a HTTP call the following way:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003Ehttps:\u002F\u002F{C2_DOMAIN}\u002Fapi\u002Frss?a=ping\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMoreover, the malware can get custom commands from the C2 server by sending commands. One example includes the \u003Cstrong\u003Eget_ck_all \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Eoperation, potential browsers for which to scrape cookies &amp; tokens\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002FPicture15.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"227\" height=\"535\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this C2 response, the \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Eresource \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003Efield also includes several Meta Graph API calls that can be used to gain information about the Facebook accounts of the victim:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads16.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"624\" height=\"388\" srcset=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002Fsize\u002Fw600\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads16.png 600w, https:\u002F\u002Fblogapp.bitdefender.com\u002Flabs\u002Fcontent\u002Fimages\u002F2024\u002F10\u002Fads16.png 624w\"\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is already becoming obvious that a core functionality of the Infostealer is to gather information about potential Facebook pages that could be used in the malicious process or sold on the dark web.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"evasion-tactics\"\u003EEvasion Tactics\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe adaptability of the cybercriminals behind these attacks makes the SYS01 Infostealer campaign especially dangerous. They use advanced evasion tactics to keep the infostealer hidden from cybersecurity tools. The malware employs sandbox detection, halting its operations if it detects it’s being run in a controlled environment, often used by analysts to examine malware. This allows it to remain undetected in many cases. In this specific case, anti-sandbox checks are made before the execution of every main component: the Javascript Unpacker, the PHP script that ensures persistence and the PHP Infostealer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen cybersecurity firms begin to flag and block a specific version of the loader, the hackers respond swiftly by updating the code. They then push out new ads with updated malware that evades the latest security measures.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"cybercriminals%E2%80%99-business-model\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECybercriminals’ Business Model\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe success of this campaign is driven by a highly structured business model that makes this malicious operation self-sustaining:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHijacking Facebook Accounts to Power the Attack\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA key goal of SYS01InfoStealer is to harvest Facebook credentials, specifically Facebook Business accounts. Once hackers gain access to these accounts, they don’t just exploit the personal data; they use the hijacked accounts to launch more malicious ads.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith access to Facebook’s advertising tools through compromised accounts, cybercriminals can create new malicious ads at scale without arousing suspicion. By using legitimate Facebook Business accounts, the ads appear more credible and bypass the usual security filters. This allows the attack to spread further, reaching more victims with each new wave of ads.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScaling the Attack\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hijacked Facebook accounts serve as a foundation for scaling up the entire operation. Each compromised account can be repurposed to promote additional malicious ads, amplifying the reach of the campaign without the hackers needing to create new Facebook accounts themselves. This is a cost-effective and time-efficient way to consistently drive traffic to malicious downloads. Being in the malvertising business isn’t just cost-effective – it also allows threat actors to stay under the radar and not rely on traditional or more obvious methods to compromise accounts, such as email phishing campaigns.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERevenue and Data Theft\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to using hijacked accounts to fund and promote their campaigns, cybercriminals can also monetize the stolen credentials by selling them on underground marketplaces, with Facebook Business accounts being highly valuable. The stolen personal information, including login data, financial info, and security tokens, can be sold to other malicious actors who may attempt to use it to fuel identity theft crimes and other attacks, turning each new victim into a revenue stream.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"indicators-of-compromise\"\u003EIndicators of
